    b.
        Sodium and Lithium both have a single valence (outer shell) electron.
        
        Sodium is more reactive than lithium because the valence electron of sodium is further away from the nucleus than the valence electron of lithium. Since the negatively charged electron and the positively charged protons in the nucleus are further apart, there is less attraction between them in sodium, so the electron is more easily lost. Sodium ionises by losing an electron, so since the electron is more easily lost, it is more reactive.
