            Kerosene can be obtained from crude oil via fractional distillation. This is when crude oil is heated until it evaporates, and is passed through a fractioning column. Since Kerosene has a unique boiling temperature (lower than diesel and higher than gasoline), and since the evaporated mixture cools down as it ascends the column, the kerosene part of the mixture condenses at the kerosene fraction, which can be removed to obtain kerosene.
