            mol = mass/RFM, so RFM * mol = mass, so 0.025 * 367 = 9.175 ~= 9
    c.
        i.
            Lead (II) bromide needs to be molten rather than solid for electrolysis to occur because electrolysis involves the movement of electricity; i.e. that the electrolyte must be able to conduct electricity. A solid ionic compound such as solid lead(II) bromide has no ions or electrons that are free to move to carry charge, so cannot conduct electricity. In contrast, a liquid ionic compound such as liquid (molten) lead(II) bromide has ions which are free to move to carry charge.
        ii.
            A suitable material for the electrodes would be platinum as it has a high melting point but is also non-reactive.
